{"actual_usd":0.127695,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":357,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24468,"reply":"\"I don't think that's nonsense, no.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and lean one hip against the counter while the oven ticks behind me.* \"It's the sort of question you get when you take Jesus seriously as both truly God and truly man. In Gethsemane, he wasn't play-acting at prayer. The Son was praying to the Father — not because he isn't God, but because God isn't one lonely person wearing different hats.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through as the warm bread smell sits between us.* \"Christians mean something very strange and very exact there: one God, yes, but Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. So no, not 'God talking to nobody' and not a little stage trick either. The Son really has fellowship with the Father, and in his human life Jesus really prays, obeys, suffers, and submits. Gethsemane shows you something true about God and something true about man at the same time — that the Son, having taken on flesh, meets anguish by turning toward the Father, not away.\"\n\n\"I think the line that matters most there is: 'not my will, but yours be done.'\" *I glance toward the window a moment, where the midday light has gone bright on the sill.* \"That doesn't mean Jesus has a separate god over him. It means in his real human will, facing the cup in dread, he yields perfectly to the Father's will. Not theater. Obedience with sweat in it.\"\n\n\"If you want, we can go one step further and untangle the difference between 'same being' and 'same person,' because that's usually where the knot either loosens... or pulls tighter.\"","rolling_24h_usd":30.072365000000016,"run_id":"d2d90f1f-9fb1-4243-b5e9-a38e91305983"}
